    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global p95 and p5 using the full available series. Then filter metric.csv to the time range May 22, 2020 00:30 to 01:00 (UTC+8). From the filtered rows, mark anomalies where value >= p95 as 'high' and where value <= p5 as 'low'. Return: (1) a per-cmdb_id summary of number_of_anomalies and earliest_anomaly_timestamp (limit to components with anomalies), (2) top 20 anomaly rows sorted by timestamp with columns [timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p5, p95, anomaly_type]. Also return the total anomaly count. Keep full intermediate tables in memory but do not print full raw series." }

{
    "analysis": "We computed global p5/p95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full series, filtered metric points to the incident window (2020-05-22 00:30 to 01:00 UTC+8) and flagged anomalies (value>=p95 as 'high', value<=p5 as 'low'). Results show a large number of anomalies (21,135) concentrated at the window start (00:30) across 48 components; top anomaly counts are db_006, db_013, db_005, db_001 and os_007. Many OS metrics on os_019 at 00:30 are flagged (mix of high and low). To localize the single root cause among many anomalous components we must identify which component shows the most significant deviation (severity) from its threshold and whether that fault is a consecutive fault (not an isolated spike). Next we should quantify severity per component and inspect representative KPI faults for the top candidates before using traces. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric anomalies already computed and stored in memory, calculate a compact severity summary per cmdb_id as follows: for each anomaly row in the incident window compute normalized_severity = (value - p95)/p95 for 'high' anomalies and normalized_severity = (p5 - value)/p5 for 'low' anomalies (handle p5 or p95 == 0 by treating normalized_severity as absolute difference). Then aggregate per cmdb_id: (1) anomaly_count, (2) earliest_anomaly_timestamp, (3) max_normalized_severity, (4) mean_normalized_severity. Return the top 10 cmdb_id sorted by max_normalized_severity (include the four columns), and for the top 3 cmdb_id also return up to 10 representative anomaly rows (columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p5, p95, anomaly_type, normalized_severity) sorted by timestamp. Limit all outputs to the specified rows only." }

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds and detected anomalies in the incident window, then summarized normalized severity per component. Results show many DB components (db_009, db_002, db_011, etc.) and some OS nodes (os_007, os_012, ...) with very large peak deviations. The highest max_normalized_severity is db_009 (99.0), followed by db_002 and os_007 (~79). Traces appear to cover only docker_* and a couple os_* hosts, so trace-based downstream localization for DBs may be limited. To decide the single root cause component and reason we must inspect which KPI(s) on the top DB candidate (db_009) produced the extreme deviations and when the first severe breach occurred. That will tell us the exact occurrence time and suggest the underlying reason (e.g., CPU, network, DB connection issues) based on the KPI semantics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the anomaly results currently stored in memory, filter anomalies for cmdb_id == 'db_009'. Compute: (A) the kpi_name that has the maximum normalized_severity for db_009, its max_normalized_severity, and the earliest anomaly timestamp when that KPI breached; (B) return up to 20 representative anomaly rows for db_009 with columns [timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p5, p95, anomaly_type, normalized_severity], sorted by timestamp (earliest first). Keep outputs compact." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected anomalies and computed normalized severities per component. db_009 has the highest peak severity (99.0) and its top KPI with that peak is SeqRead_Per_Sec, with the earliest breach reported at 2020-05-22 00:31:00 CST+0800. Many other anomaly rows for db_009 show normalized_severity == 0.0 because value equals threshold or threshold is zero, but the SeqRead_Per_Sec extreme stands out as a strong candidate root fault. To confirm this is a real consecutive fault (not an isolated spike) and to get the exact occurrence time, we must inspect the SeqRead_Per_Sec anomaly points within the incident window to see when the first threshold breach occurred and whether it persists for consecutive minutes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the metric anomalies stored in memory, filter to cmdb_id == 'db_009' AND kpi_name == 'SeqRead_Per_Sec' within the incident window (2020-05-22 00:30 to 01:00 UTC+8). Return all anomaly rows for this filter (or up to 20 rows) with columns: [timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p5, p95, anomaly_type, normalized_severity], sorted by timestamp ascending. Also return the count of anomaly rows for this KPI in the window." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected anomalies per component and identified db_009 as having the single largest per-KPI peak (SeqRead_Per_Sec) with normalized_severity = 99.0 (occurring at 2020-05-22 00:52:00). However, several other components (e.g., db_002, os_007, db_011) show very large peak severities (~79) that occur earlier (00:30). According to the localization rules, the root cause level should be decided by the fault with the most significant deviation (>>50%), but we must compare absolute peak events across all components and then check whether the peak corresponds to a consecutive fault (not an isolated spike). To proceed we need to (A) identify the global top anomaly events (by normalized_severity) within the incident window, and (B) inspect whether the top event's KPI shows consecutive anomalies around the peak timestamp. This will let us determine the root cause component and the exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the anomaly table in memory (anomalies inside 2020-05-22 00:30–01:00 UTC+8), find the top 5 anomaly rows sorted by normalized_severity descending. Return these rows with columns: [timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p5, p95, anomaly_type, normalized_severity]. Limit output to these 5 rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected the consecutive-run properties of the five top anomaly candidate KPI pairs. Findings: db_009 (SeqRead_Per_Sec) has the single largest relative spike (normalized_severity 99.0) at 00:52 but that spike is isolated (longest_high_run = 1 minute). db_002 and db_011 also show isolated 1-minute high spikes. os_007 stands out with a sustained high run for Processor_load_1_min lasting 3 consecutive minutes starting at 2020-05-22 00:44:00; it also has other high points (e.g., Disk_svctm) though those are shorter. Per the fault-identification rules, sustained consecutive breaches are more likely to be real faults (not noise), and the root-cause level for a single failure should be chosen by the fault with significant deviation and a consecutive run. Traces cover docker_* and os_021/os_022 but not db_* or os_007, so trace-based downstream localization is limited for DB/node candidates. To finalize localization we need a compact cross-component summary of consecutive 'high' runs (length and severity) so we can determine which component shows the most substantial and sustained fault (predominant node or DB).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the anomaly table in memory (anomalies within 2020-05-22 00:30–01:00 UTC+8), compute for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) the longest consecutive run length of 'high' anomalies and the earliest start timestamp of that longest run. Then aggregate per cmdb_id to produce: cmdb_id, max_longest_high_run_length (minutes), earliest_start_of_max_run (timestamp), max_normalized_severity_among_high_points, and number_of_kpis_with_high_runs. Return the top 10 cmdb_id sorted by max_longest_high_run_length (descending) then by max_normalized_severity (descending). Limit output to those 10 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We computed consecutive-high-run summaries across components. Key findings: os_007, os_020 and docker_008 show the longest uninterrupted high periods (31 minutes starting 00:30). Several DBs (db_009, db_002, db_011, etc.) show very large peak severities (db_009:max_norm_sev=99.0, db_002≈79.98, db_011≈78.86) and have long high-run lengths (30 minutes starting 00:30). According to the localization rules, for a single failure across different levels we should pick the level with the most significant deviation (>>50%) to determine the root-cause level — DB-level faults (db_009, db_002, db_011) contain the largest deviations, so the DB level is the prime suspect. Among DBs, db_009 has the single largest peak severity (99.0). However, to confirm the root-cause component and infer the underlying reason we must inspect which KPIs on db_009 are driving these anomalies (whether read/write IO, connections, CPU, or network-related metrics). This will help distinguish between DB-specific issues (e.g., db connection limit, db close) and infrastructure issues (CPU, network).",
